
sample_fmc: Simple container demonstrating use of FMC in CMRT

It can read and write FMC feature space address 4, which may or may not
do something interesting depending on which target the container is run.
The container is intended to run on Zynq706 FPGA with a bitfile and on QEMU
which map the FMC feature space address 4 to the four user LEDs.

For more information about the Zynq706 LEDs, see Xilinx Zynq706 Evaluation
Board User Guide, page 58:
https://www.xilinx.com/support/documentation/boards_and_kits/zc706/ug954-zc706-eval-board-xc7z045-ap-soc.pdf

To use the container, load it and send it a command file using the
pmtest tool.

The container parses the command file and acts according to the command.
The command is a single character, followed by a possible argument. Anything
after the command and argument is ignored.

To run (load and start) container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 run sample_fmc.img

To send data to container:
cmtest data -f100 {value}

Five commands are recognized:

1x    Set LEDs state to x; x is a lowercase hex number where each bit corresponds to a single LED.
2     Get and print LEDs state
3x    Set GPIO state to x; x is a lowercase hex number where each bit corresponds to a single GPIO.
4     Get and print GPIO state
5     set the feature bits register

For example, file with following content:

1a # Set LEDs: ON OFF ON OFF

would set the LEDs and print the output, something like this:
$ cmtest data -f100 "1a"

[CLO] process_data:102: LED states: ON OFF ON OFF

2 # this is a get command

would print the current LEDs state, something like this:
$ cmtest data -f100 "2"

[CLO] recv_sic_data:103: LED states: ON OFF ON OFF

Another example :

For example, file with following content:

11 # Set LEDs: OFF OFF OFF ON

would set the LEDs and print the output , something like this:
$ cmtest data -f100 "11"

[CLO] process_data:102: LED states: OFF OFF OFF ON

Another File with following content:

2 # this is a get command

would print the current LEDs state, something like this:

[CLO] process_data:102: LED states: OFF OFF OFF ON
$ cmtest data -f100 "2"

Similarly with following content:

3a # Set GPIOs: ON OFF ON OFF

would set the GPIOs and print the output, something like this:

[CLO] process_data:143: LED states: ON OFF ON OFF
$ cmtest data -f100 "3a"

Another example with following content:

4 # this is a get command

would print the current GPIOs state, something like this:
$ cmtest data -f100 "4"

[CLO] recv_sic_data:121: LED states: ON OFF ON OFF

5 # this is a set command

would set the feature bits register to value 0x12345678
$ cmtest data -f100 "5"

Read the value in HLOS
$ cmrt -c ./board.json sysctl 0x30

To unload container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 unload
